      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey i'm looking at our quarterly reports and shrinkage is way higher than last year. how do i actually calculate the impact that this lost inventory has on our inventory turnover ratio? need to show this to my manager.",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "To calculate the impact, you'll need to adjust your Cost of Goods Sold (COGS) in the numerator of the inventory turnover formula by subtracting the value of the lost inventory due to shrinkage. The formula is typically: Inventory Turnover = COGS / Average Inventory. By using the adjusted COGS, you will reflect the true cost of goods that were effectively lost or stolen. This will show your manager a more accurate picture of how much inventory you are actually moving relative to your stock levels.",
